<br>
PCs work off the exact same formula as NPC, with one difference. We also get an extra random damage element that is dependent on STR and ATK.<br>
<br>
If you notice, your modal hit is exactly (20*DI)+DB. Your min hit is exactly DI+DB. If you use a high damage 2 hander and look at your damage histogram, you will see 1 peak at min, another peak at mode, and 18 peaks between them at intervals equal to DI.<br>
<br>
So basically there are 2 seperate random equations used to determine PC damage. Our base damage formula is the same as the NPC damage formula.  <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=14686">Graal MacBladefury</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
Crusader of Brell</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sarvisstormrunner>SarvisStormrunner</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/9/03 8:41:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1656.topic&index=89>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Incorrect</span><hr size=1> That can't be correct. While I do see 18 different numbers between my minimum and modal hits, my log was over a relatively short period of time...maybe 5 mobs or so. Now, my weapon was a Throneblade - that's 33 damage, 51 delay, the damage bonus on it is 12. That should mean that my damage interval is 33/10=3.3. Meanwhile, my minimum hit should be DI+DB, in my case 3.3+12, or 15.3 (not sure if that would round up or down) but my actual minimum hit was 21. My modal should be DI*20+DB, or 78, which it certainly was - huge spike there.<br>
<br>
Plus, having already seen 18 numbers between the modal and the minimum, 19 shouldn't even be my minimum....because calculating my DI as I would a mob, (Max damage - minimum damage)/19, we get 78-19=59, 57/19=3.1. (note that I used my modal hit instead of my maximum, as anything over the modal would be in the category of a PC hit which a mob doesn't get) And my DI is clearly 3.3, given my weapon....unless they round that down. So if my minimum is really DI+DB, or 3.3+12=15.3, then we've already seen 19 numbers between my minimum and modal.<br>
<br>
And that still wouldn't make sense, because my hits don't increase in increments of 3.1 or 3.3, or 3 or anything even close....I had hits for 19, 21, 22, 29, 31, 32, the list goes on....many of those numbers are less than 3 numbers away from each other. If my damage was calculated like a mob's damage, then my hits would be 19, 22, 25, 28, etc. I can show the logs, if anyone is interested. It's short and I fought different types of mobs at different levels, but that shouldn't matter for this experiment. If a PC does damage like a mob, then level and AC and all that shouldn't matter - that should just change the percentage chance of any given value for &quot;x&quot; being landed on. The 20 X values should remain the same<br>
<br>
So clearly, something is off here. I reinstate my theory, which is:<br>
<br>
PC damage works the same way as mob damage, with one exception. There is a chance that the PC will get a hit which takes into account his (STR+SKILL)/100 somehow. I believe that if that type of hit is scored, there is STILL a random factor, so that type of hit would actually change the damage interval for a PC. That would account for my numbers not going up by a set amount - maybe we are looking at two different sets of numbers, each going up by a different DI...one has the STR/SKILL factor involved, the other one doesn't.<br>
<br>
That would mean that when you score a hit which has your STR/SKILL factor involved, there is still a chance of getting a crappy hit, so your maximum hit is going to be reasonably uncommon...which it certainly is, in my case <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
However I am afraid that something is off there as well, because I recieved 38 different hits and only 20 of them were in the minimum-modal range. If my theory was correct, then you would expect to only see 10 numbers in the modal-maximum range, but instead we see 18 :/<br>
